            <p>I spent over a decade in tech â€” started as an engineer, moved into product management, then data analytics. PM was my longest run, close to ten years.</p>
            <p>I was good at it. But the longer I stayed, the more I felt like I was running in place. Most of my energy went into getting people to agree with me, not actually building things.</p>
            <p class="text-base md:text-lg lg:text-xl font-medium py-1 text-ink-900">At some point I asked myself: if nothing changes in five years, what does my life look like?</p>
            <p>The answer was too clear. And that clarity made me uncomfortable.</p>
            <p>In 2023, I enrolled in Minerva University's master's program. I didn't want to become that five-year-later version of myself.</p>
            <p>Even while studying, I kept thinking â€” can I build something on my own? The ideas were there. The experience was there â€” engineering, product, data. But actually shipping a complete product? Frontend, backend, database, QA, marketing. One person couldn't do all of that. It used to take a whole team.</p>
            <p class="text-base md:text-lg lg:text-xl font-medium py-1 text-ink-900">Then AI hit a tipping point.</p>
            <p>In May 2025, Claude Code launched and I was one of the first to use it. Once I started, I couldn't stop â€” someone who left engineering 14 years ago could now ship products end to end.</p>
            <p>Four months, I built a full SaaS â€” <a href="https://airesumeadvisor.com/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:underline">AI Resume Advisor</a>. Two weeks for the <a href="https://chromewebstore.google.com/detail/ai-resume-advisor-%E2%80%94-linke/iafpieelbhhlmhgjekflneciffoonkgf" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:underline">Chrome</a> and <a href="https://microsoftedge.microsoft.com/addons/detail/ai-resume-advisor-%E2%80%94-linke/ekhlndlifglmicdphldpciifohloeaek" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:underline">Edge</a> Extensions. Then three days for <a href="https://www.neatoolkit.com/en" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="text-accent hover:underline">NeatToolkit</a>, a free tool site â€” 4,000 users on day one. This personal site, two days.</p>
            <p class="text-base md:text-lg lg:text-xl font-medium py-1 text-ink-900">All solo.</p>
            <p>But the real change wasn't the products. It was having control over my own work and life for the first time.</p>
            <p>I know where I'm going. I have a workflow that runs every day. AI is the lever. Direction matters more than speed. Do the simple things, repeat, and let compounding do the rest.</p>
            <p>This site is where I document the process.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Belief -->
      <div class="mb-10 md:mb-14 lg:mb-16">
        <div class="pl-6 md:pl-8 py-4 md:py-6 border-l-4 border-accent">
          <p class="text-xl md:text-2xl lg:text-3xl font-semibold mb-3 md:mb-4 leading-snug tracking-tight text-ink-900">Direction over speed. Systems over goals.</p>
          <p class="text-sm md:text-base lg:text-lg leading-relaxed text-ink-500">Most people chase AI tools without knowing what to build. I do it the other way around â€” find the direction first, build a compounding workflow, and use AI as the lever. Repeat the simple things. Let time do the rest.</p>
